UCTURING REMINGTON SB126955385469309739639045841200113167711963 Clinton, Hillary PRO SYND WSJ-PRO-DEBT Private Equity WSJ-PRO-PE CODES_REVIEWED Chapter 11 DEBTCHAPTER11 Consumer goods DEBTCONSUMER Top News DEBTTOPNEWS PECONSUMERGOODS North America PEREGIONSNORTHAMERICA PETOPNEWS Pro Bankruptcy Bankruptcy </DescField><DescField fid="ipccodj">BEN </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Pro Bankruptcy</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Gun Maker Remington Seeks Bankruptcy Protection; Private equity-backed gun maker is facing a heavy debt load, falling sales and lawsuits tied to Sandy Hook school shooting</Para></Headline></Title><Corrections fid="cx"><Para>Corrections &amp; Amplifications</Para><Para>Remington is being advised by Alvarez &amp; Marsal North America LLC. An earlier version of this story said it was being advised by Alvarez &amp; Marsal Capital Partners. (March 28)</Para></Corrections><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Firearms maker Remington Outdoor Co. sought bankruptcy protection Sunday, in the face of a heavy debt load, falling sales and lawsuits tied to the Sandy Hook school shooting.</Para><Para>Remington filed for chapter 11 protection in the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Wilmington, Del., with plans to hand over control of the company to its creditors—including Franklin Resources Inc. and JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co.'s asset-management division—in exchange for wiping much of its debt from its balance sheet.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>The chapter 11 filing, <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/massive-debt-roller-coaster-sales-drive-private-equity-backed-gun-maker-into-bankruptcy-1520946453?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=1">announced last month</ELink>, was delayed after <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/shooting-at-florida-high-school-authorities-report-1518638881">a Feb. 14 school shooting</ELink> in Parkland, Fla., that left 17 dead and <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/parkland-activists-inspire-newtown-teens-to-join-gun-control-movement-1521733101?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=6">reawakened the national debate</ELink> surrounding gun regulations, people familiar with the matter told The Wall Street Journal.</Para><Para>Founded in 1816, Remington is one of America's oldest and largest gun and ammunition manufacturers. The Madison, N.C., company plans to continue operations and paying its vendors and employees while under bankruptcy protection.</Para><Para>The bankruptcy filing brings to an end private-equity backer Cerberus Capital Management LP's investment in the gun business. The buyout firm acquired Bushmaster Firearms International in 2006, and in 2007 it paid $118 million for Remington and assumed $252 million of its debt. Cerberus later formed Freedom Group Inc., a holding company comprising Bushmaster, Remington and other firearms makers.</Para><Para>In the ensuing years Cerberus would experience a series of ups-and-downs with the company. Cerberus had planned to take the company public, but a number of management and manufacturing setbacks complicated efforts to revamp operations.</Para><Para>In December 2012, a Bushmaster rifle was used to kill 20 children and six staff members at Sandy Hook Elementary School in Newtown, Conn. A few years after the shooting, nine families of victims filed a wrongful-death lawsuit against Remington, alleging the gun maker was liable for producing and selling a weapon unfit for civilian use. The matter has since reached the Supreme Court in Connecticut, and the gun industry <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-court-case-making-gun-makers-anxious-1521192601">anxiously awaits the decision</ELink>.</Para><Para>Cerberus attempted to sell Remington at the urging of investors and, in 2015, separated Remington Outdoor Co. from its funds and <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cerberus-capital-to-allow-investors-to-sell-stakes-in-gun-business-1431733796">gave investors the opportunity to cash out</ELink> of the company.</Para><Para>Although Remington has reached a deal to hand over control to its creditors, the new owners plan to unload the asset to another buyer as soon as they can do so profitably, The Wall Street Journal previously reported.</Para><Para>The bankruptcy comes as the gun industry deals <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gun-sales-muted-after-parkland-shooting-store-owners-say-1520278675">with flagging demand</ELink> and a glut of stock after boosting output ahead of the 2016 presidential election, where a victory for Hillary Clinton was expected to trigger tougher ownership rules.</Para><Para>In court filings, the company listed the government's pension insurer—the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp., which is responsible for failed private-sector pension plans—and the pension plan for its Marlin firearms subsidiary as its largest unsecured creditors.</Para><Para>The company is being advised by law firm Milbank, Tweed, Hadley &amp; McCloy LLP, investment bank Lazard, and financial adviser Alvarez &amp; Marsal North America LLC.</Para><Para>Sharon Terlep contributed to this article.</Para><Para>Write to Lillian Rizzo at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:Lillian.Rizzo@wsj.com">Lillian.Rizzo@wsj.com</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-court-case-making-gun-makers-anxious-1521192601?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=2">The Court Case Making Gun Makers Anxious</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gun-sales-muted-after-parkland-shooting-store-owners-say-1520278675?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=8">Gun Sales Muted After Parkland Shooting, Store Owners Say</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Lillian Rizzo </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gun-maker-remington-seeks-bankruptcy-protection-1522025682" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

